volves executing missed runs, that might require Integration testing to verify the full flow works end-to-end, not just that the policy decision is correct. in the backfill execution. Integration testing would verify the complete flow: system downtime, missed run detection, policy application, and the actual outcome in the schedule.\n\nThe decision itself might pass unit tests, but if the implementation doesn't correctly apply that decision to the job's state, the bug surfaces only at integration level. Since the behavior describes determining and implementing the policy outcome, I need integration coverage to catch execution failures. I'll mark this as Integration.\n\nFor the confidence levels, I'm fairly certain about behaviors 1-3 being unit-testable. Behavior 4 clearly requires integration since it involves multiple components. Behavior 5 sits between unit and integration—the decision logic could be unit-tested in isolation, but verifying it actually affects the schedule requires integration. I'll assign: Behavior 1 at 0.95 Unit; Behavior 2 at 0.90 Unit with 0.10 Integration; Behavior 3 at 0.90 Unit with 0.10 Integration; Behavior 4 at 0.85 Integration, 0.10 System, 0.05 Unit; and Behavior 5 at 0.75 Integration, 0.20 Unit, 0.05 System. level is almost certainly Unit. Could need Integration if implementation has bugs that only show up with real time library. Confidence: 0.90 Unit, 0.10 Integration\n\nOverlap detector is also pure comparison logic with no I/O, so Unit testing should suffice unless the detector fetches schedules from a database, which would bump it to Integration (0.90 Unit, 0.10 Integration). DST transitions are different—they require actual timezone libraries and tzdata files, making Integration the minimum level since I can't adequately mock timezone behavior without risking real bugs. System testing might be needed if OS-level behavior is involved, but file I/O suggests Integration is sufficient (0.85 Integration, 0.10 System, 0.05 Unit if rules are hardcoded).\n\nFor the missed-run policy, the decision logic alone could be Unit, but since it determines whether to skip or backfill, executing that action in the context of actual schedule state suggests Integration is safer (0.70 Integration, 0.25 Unit, 0.05 System). All confidence distributions sum to 1.0 across the five behaviors.\n\nInvalid cron expression rejection is pure string validation and parsing with no I/O or external dependencies, so Unit testing is the appropriate minimum level.  Comprehensive input coverage—valid expressions, each invalid category (invalid month, day, hour), and edge cases like month 13 or day 32—catches real failures like off-by-one bugs in range checks. No mocking or dependencies are needed; the failure boundary is simply whether the parser correctly validates against cron format rules.\n\nNext-run-time calculation determines correct timestamps for standard cron expressions.\n\nThis is deterministic computation with no external dependencies or I/O. The failure boundary is whether the calculator correctly transforms a cron expression and start time into future run times. Unit tests with various cron patterns and dates can catch off-by-one bugs, leap year errors, and boundary condition failures. Real failures in this logic are purely computational and testable in isolation.\n\nTest coverage should include standard intervals (every hour, every day, every month), complex patterns (last day of month, nearest weekday), and edge cases (Feb 29 in leap years, month boundaries, DST dates as input). Parametrized tests with multiple date ranges verify both single next-run and next-N-runs calculations.\n\nThe only way a real failure could slip through is if the underlying time library has bugs, but that's external to the calculator logic itself.\n\nFor overlap detection, I'm looking at pure comparison and interval logic between two pre-computed run-time sequences. There's no I/O, state mutations, or external dependencies involved. The failure boundary is whether the comparison correctly identifies when two schedules would fire within the configured minimum gap. Unit tests with various schedule pairs—including no overlap, overlap within gap, overlap at gap boundary, and multiple overlaps—can catch off-by-one errors in gap calculation and boundary condition bugs. Reported conflict windows need to be verified as correct across various gap durations.\n\nDST-aware timezone scheduling is different. Real failures here depend on the timezone library's DST rules, which are OS-level data that can't be mocked without hiding bugs. If I mock the timezone library to always return consistent results, I won't catch the real non-monotonic behavior during DST transitions. Integration testing with the real timezone library and local tzdata files is required to verify that jobs scheduled for times like 2:30 AM handle spring-forward gaps and fall-back ambiguities correctly.\n\nI need to create integration tests covering spring-forward transitions (testing a job scheduled for a non-existent time), fall-back transitions (testing a job scheduled for an ambiguous time), multiple timezones with different DST rules, and transitions in both hemispheres using actual transition dates from the real timezone database. Unit-level testing would miss the real non-determinism that only appears when the actual timezone library applies its rules.\n\nFor missed-run policy handling, I'm testing how the engine decides whether to skip or backfill when a job's next run time has already passed. The key is verifying the interaction between policy decision and actual schedule state—a backfill policy might generate missed runs that conflict with other jobs, or a skip policy might silently lose work. I need integration tests with real job/schedule state to check that skip policies advance the next run without creating missed runs, backfill policies compute and add missed run times correctly, and policies with multiple jobs don't create scheduli